function ch07() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 7</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Quantitative Research: Principles, Strengths, and Limitations</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define quantitative research and explain its core principles<br>• Identify the types of research questions best suited to quantitative approaches<br>• Describe the key features of quantitative data collection and analysis<br>• Evaluate the strengths and limitations of quantitative research<br>• Determine when a quantitative approach is appropriate for your study</blockquote><h2>7.1 What Is Quantitative Research?</h2>
<p>Quantitative research is a research approach that emphasises the collection and analysis of numerical data to describe, explain, predict, or control phenomena. It is grounded in the positivist and post-positivist traditions and assumes that social phenomena can be measured, quantified, and analysed using statistical techniques. The goal of quantitative research is to produce findings that are objective, replicable, and generalisable to a broader population (Bryman, 2016).</p>
<p>The quantitative approach is characterised by several distinctive features. First, it uses deductive reasoning: the researcher begins with a theory or hypothesis and designs a study to test it. Second, it relies on standardised data collection instruments, such as questionnaires, tests, and structured observations, that produce numerical data. Third, it uses statistical analysis to identify patterns, relationships, and differences in the data. Fourth, it emphasises objectivity: the researcher seeks to minimise their influence on the data and to produce findings that are independent of the researcher's perspective (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>
<p>Quantitative research is the dominant approach in many fields, including medicine, psychology, economics, and the natural sciences. It is particularly well suited to research questions that ask about the prevalence of a phenomenon, the relationship between variables, the effectiveness of an intervention, or the prediction of outcomes. When the goal is to produce evidence that can be generalised to a large population, quantitative methods are typically the most appropriate choice (Field, 2018).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 300" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THE QUANTITATIVE RESEARCH PROCESS</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="70" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Theory</text><text x="70" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Start here</text><text x="135" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="150" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="200" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Hypothesis</text><text x="200" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Testable prediction</text><text x="265" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="280" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="330" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Data Collection</text><text x="330" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Standardised</text><text x="395" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="410" y="55" width="110" height="60" rx="6" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="465" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Statistical Analysis</text><text x="465" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Test hypothesis</text><rect x="150" y="150" width="240" height="50" rx="25" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="270" y="180" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Confirm or reject hypothesis</text><line x1="465" y1="115" x2="390" y2="150" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><rect x="60" y="230" width="420" height="50" rx="8" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="250" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="10" font-weight="700">LOGIC: Deductive (theory &#8594; data &#8594; confirmation/rejection)</text><text x="270" y="268" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">The researcher starts with what is known and tests specific predictions</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 7.1 The quantitative research process follows a deductive logic from theory through hypothesis to data and analysis.</p></div>

<h2>7.2 Strengths of Quantitative Research</h2>
<p>Quantitative research has several important strengths that explain its dominance in many fields. Its greatest strength is <strong>generalisability</strong>. When a quantitative study uses a representative sample and sound methods, its findings can be generalised to the broader population from which the sample was drawn. This is essential for informing policy, practice, and decision-making at scale (Bryman, 2016).</p>
<p>A second strength is <strong>precision</strong>. Quantitative data allow for precise measurement and comparison. You can say not just that one group performed better than another, but exactly how much better, with what degree of confidence, and with what probability that the difference is not due to chance. This precision enables the accumulation of evidence across studies, as findings can be compared and combined through techniques such as meta-analysis (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>A third strength is <strong>objectivity</strong>. Because quantitative methods use standardised instruments and statistical analysis, the findings are less susceptible to researcher bias than qualitative findings. Two researchers using the same instrument on the same sample should obtain the same results, which enhances the replicability and credibility of the research (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>
<p>A fourth strength is <strong>the ability to establish causation</strong>. Through experimental designs with random assignment, quantitative research can provide the strongest available evidence for causal claims. This makes quantitative research indispensable in fields such as medicine, public health, and education, where the effectiveness of interventions must be rigorously established (Shadish, Cook, and Campbell, 2002).</p>

<h2>7.3 Limitations of Quantitative Research</h2>
<p>Despite its strengths, quantitative research has significant limitations. The most fundamental is that it <strong>cannot capture meaning</strong>. Quantitative methods can tell you how many people reported being satisfied, but they cannot tell you what satisfaction means to those people, why they feel that way, or how their experience of satisfaction is shaped by their context and circumstances. Meaning, experience, and process are beyond the reach of numerical data (Bryman, 2016).</p>
<p>A second limitation is the <strong>artificiality of measurement</strong>. When complex social phenomena are reduced to numbers, important nuances are inevitably lost. A Likert scale measuring "anxiety" captures a single dimension of a multifaceted experience. The researcher's operationalisation of the concept may not match the way participants actually experience it, creating a gap between what is measured and what is real (Punch, 2014).</p>
<p>A third limitation is the <strong>context-stripping effect</strong>. Quantitative research typically seeks to control or eliminate contextual factors in order to isolate the effects of specific variables. While this enhances internal validity, it can reduce external validity by creating artificial conditions that do not reflect the complexity of real-world settings (Shadish, Cook, and Campbell, 2002).</p>
<p>Understanding these limitations is not an argument against quantitative research. It is an argument for choosing quantitative methods when they are appropriate and combining them with qualitative methods when the question demands a more complete picture (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Quantitative Research: Strengths and Limitations</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-2"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Strengths</h4><p>• Generalisable findings<br>• Precise measurement<br>• Objective and replicable<br>• Can establish causation<br>• Enables meta-analysis<br>• Efficient for large samples</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Limitations</h4><p>• Cannot capture meaning<br>• Artificial measurement<br>• Context-stripping effect<br>• Requires large samples<br>• May miss unexpected findings<br>• Assumes measurable reality</p></div></div></div>`;
}

function ch08() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 8</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Qualitative Research: Principles, Strengths, and Limitations</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define qualitative research and explain its core principles<br>• Identify the types of research questions best suited to qualitative approaches<br>• Describe the key features of qualitative data collection and analysis<br>• Evaluate the strengths and limitations of qualitative research<br>• Determine when a qualitative approach is appropriate for your study</blockquote><h2>8.1 What Is Qualitative Research?</h2>
<p>Qualitative research is a research approach that emphasises the collection and analysis of non-numerical data, such as words, images, and observations, to understand the meanings, experiences, and social processes that underlie human behaviour. It is grounded in the interpretivist and constructivist traditions and assumes that reality is complex, contextual, and best understood through the perspectives of those who experience it (Denzin and Lincoln, 2018).</p>
<p>The qualitative approach is characterised by several distinctive features. First, it uses inductive reasoning: the researcher begins with data and builds theory or understanding from the ground up, rather than testing a pre-existing hypothesis. Second, it relies on flexible, context-sensitive data collection methods, such as interviews, focus groups, observation, and document analysis. Third, it uses interpretive analysis to identify themes, patterns, and meanings in the data. Fourth, it embraces the role of the researcher as an active participant in the research process, acknowledging that the researcher's perspective shapes the data and its interpretation (Merriam and Tisdell, 2016).</p>
<p>Qualitative research is well suited to research questions that ask about the nature of a phenomenon, the experiences of individuals, the meanings people attach to events, or the processes through which social phenomena unfold. When the goal is to understand in depth rather than to generalise in breadth, qualitative methods are typically the most appropriate choice (Creswell and Poth, 2018).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 300" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THE QUALITATIVE RESEARCH PROCESS</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="70" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Phenomenon</text><text x="70" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Start here</text><text x="135" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="150" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="200" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Data Collection</text><text x="200" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Flexible, rich</text><text x="265" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="280" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="330" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Analysis</text><text x="330" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Themes, patterns</text><text x="395" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="410" y="55" width="110" height="60" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="465" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Understanding</text><text x="465" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Theory building</text><rect x="150" y="150" width="240" height="50" rx="25" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="270" y="180" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Emergent theory or deep understanding</text><line x1="465" y1="115" x2="390" y2="150" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><rect x="60" y="230" width="420" height="50" rx="8" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="250" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="10" font-weight="700">LOGIC: Inductive (data &#8594; patterns &#8594; theory/understanding)</text><text x="270" y="268" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">The researcher starts with the phenomenon and builds understanding from the data</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 8.1 The qualitative research process follows an inductive logic from phenomenon through data to emergent understanding.</p></div>

<h2>8.2 Strengths of Qualitative Research</h2>
<p>The greatest strength of qualitative research is its ability to capture <strong>depth and meaning</strong>. Qualitative methods allow the researcher to explore the richness and complexity of human experience in ways that numbers alone cannot. Through interviews, observation, and immersive fieldwork, qualitative researchers can access the thoughts, feelings, motivations, and interpretations of participants, providing insights that no survey can match (Denzin and Lincoln, 2018).</p>
<p>A second strength is <strong>contextual sensitivity</strong>. Qualitative research studies phenomena in their natural settings, paying attention to the social, cultural, and historical contexts that shape them. This contextual sensitivity is essential for understanding why people behave as they do, not just what they do (Merriam and Tisdell, 2016).</p>
<p>A third strength is <strong>flexibility</strong>. Qualitative research designs are iterative and adaptive. The researcher can modify their questions, methods, and focus as the study progresses, responding to unexpected findings and emerging themes. This flexibility makes qualitative research particularly valuable for exploratory studies, where the key issues are not yet well understood (Creswell and Poth, 2018).</p>
<p>A fourth strength is the ability to <strong>give voice to participants</strong>. Qualitative research presents participants' own words and perspectives, allowing their experiences to be heard and understood. This is particularly important in research with marginalised or under-represented populations, whose perspectives may be absent from quantitative datasets (Denzin and Lincoln, 2018).</p>

<h2>8.3 Limitations of Qualitative Research</h2>
<p>The most frequently cited limitation of qualitative research is <strong>limited generalisability</strong>. Because qualitative studies typically use small, purposively selected samples, their findings cannot be generalised to broader populations in the statistical sense. This is a valid concern, though qualitative researchers argue that their goal is transferability (the applicability of findings to similar contexts) rather than generalisability (Merriam and Tisdell, 2016).</p>
<p>A second limitation is the <strong>influence of the researcher</strong>. In qualitative research, the researcher is the primary instrument of data collection and analysis. This means that the researcher's assumptions, perspectives, and biases inevitably shape the data and its interpretation. While reflexivity can mitigate this influence, it cannot eliminate it entirely (Creswell and Poth, 2018).</p>
<p>A third limitation is <strong>time and resource intensity</strong>. Qualitative data collection, particularly through interviews and ethnographic fieldwork, is extremely time-consuming. Transcribing, coding, and analysing qualitative data can take hundreds of hours. This limits the scope of qualitative studies and makes them impractical for addressing questions that require large samples (Bryman, 2016).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Qualitative Research: Strengths and Limitations</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-2"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Strengths</h4><p>• Captures depth and meaning<br>• Contextually sensitive<br>• Flexible and adaptive<br>• Gives voice to participants<br>• Reveals unexpected findings<br>• Builds grounded theory</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Limitations</h4><p>• Limited generalisability<br>• Researcher influence on data<br>• Time and resource intensive<br>• Difficult to replicate<br>• Subjective analysis process<br>• Small sample sizes</p></div></div></div>`;
}

function ch09() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 9</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Mixed Methods Research: When and How to Combine Both</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define mixed methods research and explain its rationale<br>• Identify research questions that require mixed methods approaches<br>• Describe the three main mixed methods designs: convergent, explanatory sequential, and exploratory sequential<br>• Evaluate the strengths and challenges of mixed methods research<br>• Design a mixed methods study with appropriate integration of quantitative and qualitative components</blockquote><h2>9.1 What Is Mixed Methods Research?</h2>
<p>Mixed methods research is an approach that combines quantitative and qualitative methods within a single study or programme of research. It is not simply the parallel use of two methods; it is the intentional integration of both types of data to produce a more complete understanding of a research problem than either approach could achieve alone. The defining feature of mixed methods research is integration: the quantitative and qualitative components must be deliberately combined, not merely conducted side by side (Creswell and Plano Clark, 2018).</p>
<p>The rationale for mixed methods research rests on the principle of complementarity. Quantitative methods are strong where qualitative methods are weak, and vice versa. Quantitative methods provide breadth, precision, and generalisability; qualitative methods provide depth, context, and meaning. By combining both, the researcher can address the limitations of each approach and produce findings that are both broadly applicable and deeply informative (Tashakkori and Teddlie, 2010).</p>
<p>Mixed methods research has grown rapidly in popularity over the past two decades, particularly in fields such as health sciences, education, and social policy, where research problems are complex and multidimensional. It is now recognised as a legitimate third approach, alongside quantitative and qualitative research, rather than as an inferior compromise between the two (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 320" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THREE CORE MIXED METHODS DESIGNS</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="160" height="240" rx="8" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="100" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10" font-weight="700">CONVERGENT</text><line x1="40" y1="90" x2="160" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><rect x="35" y="105" width="55" height="35" rx="4" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="62" y="127" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="8">QUAN</text><rect x="105" y="105" width="55" height="35" rx="4" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="132" y="127" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="8">QUAL</text><text x="95" y="122" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="12">+</text><text x="100" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Collected at</text><text x="100" y="180" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">the same time</text><text x="100" y="200" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10">&#8595;</text><text x="100" y="220" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Merged for</text><text x="100" y="235" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">comparison</text><text x="100" y="270" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="8.5" font-weight="600">Best for: Triangulation</text><rect x="190" y="55" width="160" height="240" rx="8" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="270" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10" font-weight="700">EXPLANATORY</text><text x="270" y="93" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10" font-weight="700">SEQUENTIAL</text><line x1="210" y1="100" x2="330" y2="100" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><rect x="215" y="115" width="110" height="30" rx="4" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="270" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">QUAN first</text><text x="270" y="160" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10">&#8595;</text><rect x="215" y="170" width="110" height="30" rx="4" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="270" y="190" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">then QUAL</text><text x="270" y="225" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Qualitative data</text><text x="270" y="240" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">explains numbers</text><text x="270" y="270" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="8.5" font-weight="600">Best for: Explaining results</text><rect x="360" y="55" width="160" height="240" rx="8" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="440" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10" font-weight="700">EXPLORATORY</text><text x="440" y="93" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10" font-weight="700">SEQUENTIAL</text><line x1="380" y1="100" x2="500" y2="100" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><rect x="385" y="115" width="110" height="30" rx="4" fill="#5a4fcf" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="1"/><text x="440" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">QUAL first</text><text x="440" y="160" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10">&#8595;</text><rect x="385" y="170" width="110" height="30" rx="4" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="440" y="190" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">then QUAN</text><text x="440" y="225" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Qualitative findings</text><text x="440" y="240" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">inform measurement</text><text x="440" y="270" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="8.5" font-weight="600">Best for: Instrument dev.</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 9.1 The three core mixed methods designs and their sequencing of quantitative and qualitative components.</p></div>

<h2>9.2 Strengths and Challenges</h2>
<p>The primary strength of mixed methods research is <strong>comprehensiveness</strong>. By combining quantitative and qualitative evidence, the researcher can address research questions more fully than either approach alone permits. Quantitative data can establish the scope and scale of a phenomenon; qualitative data can explain why it occurs and what it means to those involved (Creswell and Plano Clark, 2018).</p>
<p>A second strength is <strong>triangulation</strong>. When quantitative and qualitative findings converge, confidence in the results is increased. When they diverge, the researcher has an opportunity to explore why, which often leads to deeper and more nuanced understanding (Tashakkori and Teddlie, 2010).</p>
<p>The primary challenge is <strong>complexity</strong>. Mixed methods studies require the researcher to be competent in both quantitative and qualitative methods, which doubles the methodological expertise required. They also require more time, more resources, and more complex research designs than single-method studies (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>
<p>A second challenge is <strong>integration</strong>. Simply collecting both types of data is not enough; they must be meaningfully integrated. Many studies that claim to be mixed methods are actually parallel studies, collecting quantitative and qualitative data separately without any genuine integration. True mixed methods research requires a deliberate strategy for combining the two types of evidence (Creswell and Plano Clark, 2018).</p>`;
}

function ch10() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 10</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Making the Choice: A Decision Framework for Your Approach</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Apply a systematic decision framework to select your research approach<br>• Match question types to appropriate approaches<br>• Consider practical constraints such as time, resources, and access<br>• Articulate and defend your choice of approach in a methodology chapter<br>• Avoid common pitfalls in approach selection</blockquote><h2>10.1 A Systematic Decision Process</h2>
<p>Choosing between quantitative, qualitative, and mixed methods approaches is one of the most consequential decisions in research design. This chapter provides a systematic framework for making that choice, based on the nature of your research question, the type of evidence needed, the philosophical assumptions of your study, and the practical constraints you face (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>
<p>The decision process has four steps. First, examine your research question. What kind of answer does it seek? If it seeks a numerical answer (how many, how much, what predicts), a quantitative approach is indicated. If it seeks an interpretive answer (how, why, what is the experience), a qualitative approach is indicated. If it seeks both, a mixed methods approach may be appropriate (Punch, 2014).</p>
<p>Second, consider the state of knowledge in your area. If the phenomenon is well understood and established theories exist, a quantitative approach that tests specific hypotheses may be most productive. If the phenomenon is poorly understood and no adequate theory exists, a qualitative approach that explores and builds understanding may be more appropriate. If some aspects are well understood while others are not, a mixed methods approach can address both (Creswell and Plano Clark, 2018).</p>
<p>Third, consider your philosophical assumptions. Are you more comfortable with a realist ontology and objectivist epistemology (quantitative)? Or a relativist ontology and subjectivist epistemology (qualitative)? Or a pragmatic approach that transcends these distinctions (mixed methods)? While your philosophical assumptions should not override the demands of your research question, they should be consistent with your chosen approach (Crotty, 1998).</p>
<p>Fourth, consider practical constraints. How much time do you have? What resources are available? Do you have access to the participants or data sources needed for your chosen approach? Can you competently execute the methods required? Practical constraints should not determine your approach, but they may narrow your options (Punch, 2014).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 380" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">APPROACH SELECTION DECISION FRAMEWORK</text><rect x="145" y="55" width="250" height="40" rx="20" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="270" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">START: What does your question seek?</text><line x1="200" y1="95" x2="120" y2="125" stroke="#2d6a4f" stroke-width="2"/><line x1="270" y1="95" x2="270" y2="125" stroke="#5a4fcf" stroke-width="2"/><line x1="340" y1="95" x2="420" y2="125" stroke="#c9a227" stroke-width="2"/><rect x="20" y="125" width="180" height="50" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="110" y="148" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Numbers, patterns,</text><text x="110" y="163" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">predictions, causation</text><rect x="180" y="125" width="180" height="50" rx="6" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="270" y="148" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Meanings, experiences,</text><text x="270" y="163" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">processes, context</text><rect x="340" y="125" width="180" height="50" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="430" y="148" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Both breadth</text><text x="430" y="163" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="600">and depth needed</text><line x1="110" y1="175" x2="110" y2="200" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><line x1="270" y1="175" x2="270" y2="200" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><line x1="430" y1="175" x2="430" y2="200" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><rect x="30" y="200" width="160" height="35" rx="17" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="110" y="222" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">QUANTITATIVE</text><rect x="190" y="200" width="160" height="35" rx="17" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="270" y="222" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">QUALITATIVE</text><rect x="350" y="200" width="160" height="35" rx="17" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="430" y="222" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">MIXED METHODS</text><rect x="60" y="270" width="420" height="80" rx="8" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="295" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="10" font-weight="700">THEN CHECK:</text><text x="270" y="315" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Is your approach consistent with your paradigm?</text><text x="270" y="332" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Do you have the time, resources, and skills to execute it?</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 10.1 A systematic decision framework for selecting your research approach.</p></div>

<h2>10.2 Defending Your Choice</h2>
<p>Whatever approach you choose, you must be able to justify it. Your justification should address three questions. Why is this approach the best fit for your research question? Why is it consistent with your philosophical assumptions? And why is it feasible given your constraints? The justification should be substantive, not formulaic. Simply stating that you chose a qualitative approach because you want to understand meanings is not sufficient; you must explain why your specific question requires this kind of understanding and why other approaches would be inadequate (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>
<p>The most convincing justifications acknowledge the alternatives. Rather than presenting your chosen approach as the only possibility, explain why you considered other approaches and why you rejected them. This demonstrates that your choice was deliberate and informed, not arbitrary or habitual (Punch, 2014).</p>`;
}

function ch11() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 11</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Experimental and Quasi-Experimental Designs</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define experimental and quasi-experimental designs and distinguish between them<br>• Identify the essential features of a true experiment: manipulation, control, and random assignment<br>• Describe common quasi-experimental designs and their applications<br>• Evaluate the internal and external validity of experimental designs<br>• Determine when experimental or quasi-experimental designs are appropriate for your research</blockquote><h2>11.1 The Logic of Experimentation</h2>
<p>The experiment is the gold standard for establishing causal relationships in research. Its logic is simple and elegant: if you want to know whether X causes Y, you manipulate X, hold everything else constant, and observe whether Y changes. If it does, and if you have adequately controlled for alternative explanations, you can conclude that X caused the change in Y. This logic of controlled comparison is the foundation of experimental design (Campbell and Stanley, 1963).</p>
<p>A true experiment has three essential features. The first is <strong>manipulation</strong>: the researcher actively controls the independent variable, applying different levels or conditions to different groups. The second is <strong>control</strong>: the researcher holds all other variables constant, so that any observed difference in the dependent variable can be attributed to the manipulation of the independent variable rather than to extraneous factors. The third is <strong>random assignment</strong>: participants are allocated to experimental and control groups by a random process, which ensures that the groups are equivalent at the start of the experiment (Shadish, Cook, and Campbell, 2002).</p>
<p>Random assignment is the feature that distinguishes a true experiment from a quasi-experiment. It is also the most powerful tool for controlling confounding variables, because it distributes all participant characteristics, both known and unknown, equally across groups. Without random assignment, differences between groups at the start of the study can provide alternative explanations for any differences observed at the end (Campbell and Stanley, 1963).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 320" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">TRUE EXPERIMENT: THE CLASSIC DESIGN</text><rect x="150" y="55" width="240" height="35" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="270" y="78" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Population of participants</text><line x1="270" y1="90" x2="270" y2="105" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><rect x="195" y="105" width="150" height="30" rx="15" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="270" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">RANDOM ASSIGNMENT</text><line x1="220" y1="135" x2="130" y2="165" stroke="#2d6a4f" stroke-width="2"/><line x1="320" y1="135" x2="410" y2="165" stroke="#8b3a3a" stroke-width="2"/><rect x="40" y="165" width="180" height="50" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="130" y="185" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Experimental Group</text><text x="130" y="203" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.8)" font-size="9">Receives treatment (X)</text><rect x="320" y="165" width="180" height="50" rx="6" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="410" y="185" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Control Group</text><text x="410" y="203" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.8)" font-size="9">No treatment</text><line x1="130" y1="215" x2="130" y2="240" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><line x1="410" y1="215" x2="410" y2="240" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><rect x="50" y="240" width="160" height="30" rx="6" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="130" y="260" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">Measure outcome (Y)</text><rect x="330" y="240" width="160" height="30" rx="6" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="410" y="260" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">Measure outcome (Y)</text><rect x="140" y="290" width="260" height="30" rx="15" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="310" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Compare outcomes: Did X cause change in Y?</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 11.1 The classic true experimental design with random assignment, treatment, and control groups.</p></div>

<h2>11.2 Quasi-Experimental Designs</h2>
<p>In many real-world research contexts, true experiments are not feasible. Researchers may not be able to randomly assign participants to conditions (for example, you cannot randomly assign students to different schools), or they may not be able to manipulate the independent variable (for example, you cannot experimentally manipulate someone's socioeconomic status). In these cases, quasi-experimental designs provide an alternative that retains some of the logic of experimentation while relaxing the requirement for random assignment (Shadish, Cook, and Campbell, 2002).</p>
<p>Common quasi-experimental designs include the <strong>non-equivalent control group design</strong>, in which two existing groups (such as two classrooms or two hospitals) are compared, with one receiving the treatment and the other serving as a control. The key difference from a true experiment is that the groups were not formed by random assignment, so they may differ in systematic ways that could confound the results. Researchers can address this threat through matching, statistical controls, or pre-testing (Campbell and Stanley, 1963).</p>
<p>Another common design is the <strong>interrupted time series design</strong>, in which the researcher measures the outcome variable at multiple points before and after the introduction of an intervention. If the pattern of the outcome changes at the point of intervention, and the change cannot be attributed to other events occurring at the same time, the intervention is likely responsible. This design is particularly useful for evaluating policy changes and public health interventions (Shadish, Cook, and Campbell, 2002).</p>

<h2>11.3 Internal and External Validity</h2>
<p>Two concepts are central to evaluating experimental designs: internal validity and external validity. <strong>Internal validity</strong> refers to the degree to which the study's design allows the researcher to conclude that the independent variable caused the observed change in the dependent variable. Threats to internal validity include confounding variables, selection bias, maturation, history effects, and testing effects. True experiments with random assignment have the highest internal validity (Campbell and Stanley, 1963).</p>
<p><strong>External validity</strong> refers to the degree to which the study's findings can be generalised to other settings, populations, and conditions. There is often a tension between internal and external validity: the more tightly controlled an experiment is, the higher its internal validity but the lower its external validity, because the controlled conditions may not reflect the complexity and variability of real-world settings (Shadish, Cook, and Campbell, 2002).</p>
<p>The researcher's task is to balance these two forms of validity, maximising internal validity while maintaining sufficient external validity for the findings to be useful beyond the specific study context. This balancing act is at the heart of experimental design (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Experimental vs. Quasi-Experimental Designs</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-2"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>True Experiment</h4><p><strong>Random assignment:</strong> Yes<br><strong>Internal validity:</strong> High<br><strong>Control of confounds:</strong> Strong<br><strong>Feasibility:</strong> Often limited<br><strong>Example:</strong> RCT in clinical trial</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Quasi-Experiment</h4><p><strong>Random assignment:</strong> No<br><strong>Internal validity:</strong> Moderate<br><strong>Control of confounds:</strong> Partial<br><strong>Feasibility:</strong> More practical<br><strong>Example:</strong> Comparing existing groups</p></div></div></div>`;
}

function ch12() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 12</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Survey Design: Cross-Sectional and Longitudinal</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define survey research and explain its role in quantitative inquiry<br>• Distinguish between cross-sectional and longitudinal survey designs<br>• Design a survey study that addresses your research question<br>• Evaluate the strengths and limitations of survey research<br>• Avoid common pitfalls in survey design</blockquote><h2>12.1 The Nature of Survey Research</h2>
<p>Survey research is the most widely used research design in the social sciences. It involves the systematic collection of data from a sample of individuals, typically through questionnaires or structured interviews, to describe or explain features of a population. Surveys are versatile, efficient, and capable of gathering data from large numbers of respondents, making them the design of choice for many descriptive and relational research questions (De Vaus, 2014).</p>
<p>Despite its ubiquity, survey research is frequently misunderstood. Many researchers treat surveys as simple data collection tools rather than as research designs with their own logic, requirements, and limitations. A well-designed survey is far more than a list of questions; it is a carefully constructed instrument embedded within a research design that specifies how the sample will be selected, how the data will be collected, and how the results will be analysed (Fowler, 2014).</p>
<p>The two main types of survey design are cross-sectional and longitudinal. Cross-sectional surveys collect data from a sample at a single point in time. Longitudinal surveys collect data from the same sample (or comparable samples) at multiple points in time. The choice between them depends on the research question: cross-sectional designs are appropriate for describing the current state of a phenomenon, while longitudinal designs are necessary for studying change over time (De Vaus, 2014).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 280" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">CROSS-SECTIONAL vs. LONGITUDINAL SURVEYS</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="240" height="200" rx="8" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="140" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">CROSS-SECTIONAL</text><line x1="40" y1="90" x2="240" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><text x="140" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Data collected ONCE</text><text x="140" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Snapshot in time</text><text x="140" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Describes current state</text><text x="140" y="175" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Cannot track change</text><text x="140" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Faster and cheaper</text><text x="140" y="225" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Best for: prevalence,</text><text x="140" y="240" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9" font-weight="600">associations, description</text><rect x="280" y="55" width="240" height="200" rx="8" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="400" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">LONGITUDINAL</text><line x1="300" y1="90" x2="500" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><text x="400" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Data collected MULTIPLE times</text><text x="400" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Tracks change over time</text><text x="400" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Can identify trends</text><text x="400" y="175" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Stronger causal evidence</text><text x="400" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">More time and resources</text><text x="400" y="225" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Best for: change, development,</text><text x="400" y="240" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9" font-weight="600">causal ordering</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 12.1 Cross-sectional surveys provide a snapshot; longitudinal surveys track change over time.</p></div>

<h2>12.2 Designing an Effective Survey</h2>
<p>Effective survey design requires attention to several critical elements. The <strong>sampling strategy</strong> determines who is surveyed and how representative the results are. Probability sampling (random, stratified, cluster) allows generalisation to the population; non-probability sampling (convenience, purposive, snowball) limits generalisability but may be more practical (Fowler, 2014).</p>
<p>The <strong>questionnaire design</strong> determines the quality of the data. Questions must be clear, unambiguous, and relevant to the research question. Response options must be exhaustive and mutually exclusive. The order and wording of questions can introduce bias if not carefully managed. Pilot testing is essential for identifying problems before the main data collection (De Vaus, 2014).</p>
<p>The <strong>mode of administration</strong> affects response rates and data quality. Options include face-to-face interviews, telephone interviews, postal questionnaires, and online surveys. Each mode has advantages and disadvantages in terms of cost, speed, response rate, and the types of questions that can be asked. Online surveys have become the dominant mode in many fields due to their low cost and speed, but they may introduce sampling bias if the target population does not have equal access to the internet (Fowler, 2014).</p>

<h2>12.3 Limitations of Survey Research</h2>
<p>Survey research has important limitations that must be acknowledged. The most fundamental is that <strong>surveys cannot establish causation</strong>. Even with a well-designed cross-sectional survey, you can establish associations between variables but not causal relationships, because you cannot determine temporal precedence or rule out confounding variables (De Vaus, 2014).</p>
<p>A second limitation is <strong>reliance on self-report</strong>. Surveys depend on participants' willingness and ability to report their behaviour, attitudes, and experiences accurately. Social desirability bias, recall bias, and acquiescence bias can all distort survey results (Fowler, 2014).</p>
<p>A third limitation is <strong>response rate decline</strong>. Survey response rates have been declining steadily across many fields and modes of administration. Low response rates introduce the possibility of non-response bias: the people who respond may be systematically different from those who do not, compromising the representativeness of the sample (De Vaus, 2014).</p>`;
}

function ch13() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 13</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Case Study Design: Single and Multiple Cases</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define case study research and explain when it is the appropriate design choice<br>• Distinguish between single-case and multiple-case designs<br>• Identify the types of research questions best addressed by case studies<br>• Design a rigorous case study with clear boundaries, data sources, and analysis strategies<br>• Address common criticisms of case study research</blockquote><h2>13.1 What Is a Case Study?</h2>
<p>A case study is an in-depth investigation of a contemporary phenomenon within its real-world context, especially when the boundaries between phenomenon and context are not clearly evident. It is a research design, not a method; it can employ any combination of quantitative and qualitative data collection methods. What distinguishes a case study from other designs is its focus on understanding a specific case or cases in depth, within the natural context in which the case occurs (Yin, 2018).</p>
<p>The "case" in a case study can be an individual, an organisation, a programme, an event, a community, or any other bounded system that the researcher wishes to understand. The key is that the case has clear boundaries: you can specify what is included within the case and what is not. A study of "leadership in Organisation X" has a clear case (Organisation X); a study of "leadership in general" does not have a clear case and is not suitable for case study design (Stake, 1995).</p>
<p>Case studies are particularly appropriate for research questions that ask "how" or "why," that investigate contemporary events over which the researcher has little or no control, and that require detailed, contextualised understanding. They are frequently used in business, education, public administration, political science, and health services research (Yin, 2018).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 300" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">CASE STUDY DESIGNS: SINGLE vs. MULTIPLE</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="240" height="220" rx="8" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="140" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">SINGLE-CASE DESIGN</text><line x1="40" y1="90" x2="240" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><text x="140" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Focuses on ONE case in depth</text><text x="140" y="138" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Appropriate when the case is:</text><text x="140" y="158" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Critical (tests a theory)</text><text x="140" y="175" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Extreme or unique</text><text x="140" y="192" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Representative or typical</text><text x="140" y="209" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Revelatory (new access)</text><text x="140" y="226" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Longitudinal (over time)</text><text x="140" y="255" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="9" font-style="italic">Maximum depth of analysis</text><rect x="280" y="55" width="240" height="220" rx="8" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="400" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">MULTIPLE-CASE DESIGN</text><line x1="300" y1="90" x2="500" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><text x="400" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Studies TWO or more cases</text><text x="400" y="138" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Appropriate when you need:</text><text x="400" y="158" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Cross-case comparison</text><text x="400" y="175" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Replication logic</text><text x="400" y="192" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Pattern identification</text><text x="400" y="209" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Stronger generalisability</text><text x="400" y="226" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9">Theoretical development</text><text x="400" y="255" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="9" font-style="italic">More evidence, broader scope</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 13.1 Single-case designs maximise depth; multiple-case designs enable comparison and stronger evidence.</p></div>

<h2>13.2 Designing a Rigorous Case Study</h2>
<p>A rigorous case study requires careful design decisions about case selection, data sources, and analysis strategy. <strong>Case selection</strong> should be purposive and justified: why this case and not another? The rationale might be that the case is critical for testing a theory, that it is typical of a larger class of cases, or that it is extreme or unusual in ways that make it particularly informative (Yin, 2018).</p>
<p><strong>Data sources</strong> in a case study are typically multiple and diverse. Yin (2018) identifies six major sources of evidence for case studies: documents, archival records, interviews, direct observation, participant observation, and physical artefacts. Using multiple sources of evidence allows for triangulation, which strengthens the credibility of the findings (Stake, 1995).</p>
<p><strong>Analysis</strong> in a case study can take many forms, depending on the research question and the type of data collected. Common analytical strategies include pattern matching (comparing observed patterns with predicted patterns), explanation building (constructing an explanation for the case), and cross-case synthesis (comparing findings across multiple cases). The key is that the analysis is systematic, transparent, and clearly linked to the evidence (Yin, 2018).</p>

<h2>13.3 Addressing Criticisms of Case Study Research</h2>
<p>Case study research is sometimes criticised for lacking generalisability. This criticism reflects a misunderstanding of the purpose of case study research. Case studies do not aim for statistical generalisation (generalising from a sample to a population); they aim for analytical generalisation (generalising from a case to a theory). A well-designed case study can provide powerful evidence for or against a theoretical proposition, even though its findings cannot be directly generalised to a broader population (Yin, 2018).</p>
<p>A second criticism is that case studies are subjective and prone to researcher bias. This concern is addressed through rigorous design features: using multiple data sources, maintaining a chain of evidence, having key informants review the case study report, and using systematic analytical procedures. When these measures are taken, case study research can be as rigorous as any other design (Stake, 1995).</p>`;
}

function ch14() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 14</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Ethnography, Phenomenology, and Grounded Theory</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define ethnography, phenomenology, and grounded theory as qualitative research designs<br>• Identify the types of research questions each design is best suited to address<br>• Describe the data collection and analysis methods associated with each design<br>• Evaluate the strengths and limitations of each design<br>• Select the appropriate qualitative design for your research question</blockquote><h2>14.1 Ethnography</h2>
<p>Ethnography is the study of a culture-sharing group through prolonged immersion in the group's natural setting. The ethnographer spends extended periods of time with the group, observing their activities, participating in their lives, and interviewing members to understand the cultural patterns, shared meanings, and social processes that shape the group's behaviour. The goal is to produce a rich, detailed, and culturally contextualised account of the group's way of life (Hammersley and Atkinson, 2019).</p>
<p>Ethnography originated in anthropology, where it was developed as a method for studying non-Western cultures. It has since been adopted by researchers in education, health sciences, business studies, and many other fields as a powerful tool for understanding any group that shares a distinct culture, whether that group is a hospital ward, a software development team, a street gang, or an online community (Fetterman, 2020).</p>
<p>The defining feature of ethnography is <strong>prolonged engagement</strong>. The researcher does not simply visit the field; they live in it. This extended immersion allows the researcher to develop an insider's understanding of the group's culture while maintaining the outsider's perspective necessary for analysis. The tension between these two perspectives, being both participant and observer, is at the heart of ethnographic practice (Hammersley and Atkinson, 2019).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Three Qualitative Research Designs Compared</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-3"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Ethnography</h4><p><strong>Focus:</strong> Culture of a group<br><strong>Data:</strong> Observation, participation, interviews<br><strong>Duration:</strong> Months to years<br><strong>Product:</strong> Cultural description<br><strong>Question:</strong> How does this group live and make meaning?</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Phenomenology</h4><p><strong>Focus:</strong> Lived experience<br><strong>Data:</strong> In-depth interviews<br><strong>Duration:</strong> Weeks to months<br><strong>Product:</strong> Essence of experience<br><strong>Question:</strong> What is it like to experience X?</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--teal);"><h4>Grounded Theory</h4><p><strong>Focus:</strong> Social process<br><strong>Data:</strong> Interviews, observations<br><strong>Duration:</strong> Months<br><strong>Product:</strong> Emergent theory<br><strong>Question:</strong> What theory explains this process?</p></div></div></div>

<h2>14.2 Phenomenology</h2>
<p>Phenomenology is the study of lived experience. Its goal is to understand the essence of a particular experience as it is lived by those who have it. The phenomenological researcher asks: What is it like to experience this phenomenon? What are the common features of the experience that make it this particular experience and not some other? (Van Manen, 2016)</p>
<p>Phenomenological research typically involves in-depth interviews with a small number of individuals (usually 5 to 25) who have all experienced the phenomenon of interest. The interviews are long, open-ended, and focused on the participant's lived experience. The researcher then analyses the interview transcripts to identify the essential structures of the experience: the themes, patterns, and meanings that are common across participants (Moustakas, 1994).</p>
<p>Two main traditions exist within phenomenological research. <strong>Descriptive phenomenology</strong>, associated with Husserl, focuses on describing the experience as it is, setting aside the researcher's preconceptions (a process called "bracketing" or "epoché"). <strong>Interpretive phenomenology</strong> (also called hermeneutic phenomenology), associated with Heidegger and developed by Van Manen, argues that experience is always interpreted and that the researcher's perspective inevitably shapes the analysis (Van Manen, 2016).</p>

<h2>14.3 Grounded Theory</h2>
<p>Grounded theory is a research design whose primary purpose is to develop theory that is grounded in, or emerges from, the data. Rather than testing a pre-existing hypothesis, the grounded theorist begins with a broad area of interest, collects data, analyses the data, and develops a theory that is closely tied to the evidence. The resulting theory is "grounded" because it is derived from the data rather than imposed upon it (Charmaz, 2014).</p>
<p>Grounded theory was originally developed by Glaser and Strauss (1967) and has since evolved into several distinct versions. The most widely used contemporary version is Charmaz's (2014) constructivist grounded theory, which emphasises the researcher's active role in constructing theory from the data and the importance of reflexivity throughout the research process.</p>
<p>The distinctive features of grounded theory include <strong>theoretical sampling</strong> (selecting data sources based on their potential to contribute to the emerging theory), <strong>constant comparison</strong> (continuously comparing new data with previously analysed data to identify patterns and refine categories), and <strong>theoretical saturation</strong> (continuing data collection until no new themes or categories emerge). These features create an iterative, cyclical process in which data collection and analysis proceed simultaneously rather than sequentially (Charmaz, 2014).</p>`;
}

function ch15() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 15</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Action Research and Participatory Designs</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define action research and explain how it differs from other research designs<br>• Describe the cyclical process of planning, acting, observing, and reflecting<br>• Identify the types of research questions and contexts for which action research is appropriate<br>• Distinguish between different forms of action research, including participatory action research<br>• Evaluate the strengths and limitations of action research as an academic research design</blockquote><h2>15.1 What Is Action Research?</h2>
<p>Action research is a research design that combines inquiry with action. Its purpose is not merely to understand a problem but to solve it. The researcher works collaboratively with practitioners, community members, or other stakeholders to identify a problem, develop and implement an intervention, and evaluate its effects. The process is cyclical: each cycle of action and reflection informs the next, leading to progressive improvement and deepening understanding (Reason and Bradbury, 2008).</p>
<p>Action research differs from other designs in several important ways. First, it is explicitly change-oriented: the goal is not just to generate knowledge but to improve practice. Second, it is collaborative: the researcher works with, not on, the people involved in the situation being studied. Third, it is iterative: the research proceeds through repeated cycles of planning, acting, observing, and reflecting, rather than following a linear sequence from question to conclusion (McNiff, 2017).</p>
<p>Action research has its roots in the work of Kurt Lewin in the 1940s, who argued that the best way to understand a social system is to try to change it. It has since developed into a diverse family of approaches used in education, healthcare, social work, community development, and organisational management (Reason and Bradbury, 2008).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 400 400" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="200" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THE ACTION RESEARCH CYCLE</text><circle cx="200" cy="220" r="120" fill="none" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="6,4"/><rect x="150" y="85" width="100" height="40" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="200" y="110" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">1. PLAN</text><rect x="280" y="190" width="100" height="40" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="330" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">2. ACT</text><rect x="150" y="310" width="100" height="40" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="200" y="335" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">3. OBSERVE</text><rect x="20" y="190" width="100" height="40" rx="6" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="70" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">4. REFLECT</text><text x="260" y="140" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><text x="300" y="270" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8595;</text><text x="130" y="290" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8592;</text><text x="90" y="155" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8593;</text><circle cx="200" cy="220" r="35" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="200" y="216" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9" font-weight="700">REPEAT</text><text x="200" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">CYCLE</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 15.1 The action research cycle: plan, act, observe, reflect, and then repeat with refined understanding.</p></div>

<h2>15.2 Participatory Action Research</h2>
<p><strong>Participatory action research (PAR)</strong> is a form of action research that places particular emphasis on the active participation of community members or stakeholders in every stage of the research process. In PAR, the distinction between researcher and researched is deliberately blurred: community members are not passive subjects but active co-researchers who help define the research questions, collect and analyse data, and develop and implement solutions (Kindon, Pain, and Kesby, 2007).</p>
<p>PAR is grounded in principles of social justice and empowerment. It is particularly appropriate for research with marginalised or disadvantaged communities, where traditional research approaches may be experienced as extractive, exploitative, or irrelevant. By involving community members as equal partners, PAR ensures that the research addresses their priorities, respects their knowledge, and produces outcomes that benefit them directly (Reason and Bradbury, 2008).</p>

<h2>15.3 Strengths and Limitations</h2>
<p>The greatest strength of action research is its <strong>practical relevance</strong>. Because it is designed to solve real problems in real settings, its findings have immediate applicability. It also generates knowledge that is deeply contextualised and informed by the perspectives of those most affected by the problem (McNiff, 2017).</p>
<p>The primary limitation of action research is its <strong>limited generalisability</strong>. Because it is conducted in specific contexts and focused on specific problems, its findings may not be directly applicable to other settings. It also faces challenges related to rigour: the close involvement of the researcher in the situation being studied can make it difficult to maintain analytical distance, and the iterative nature of the process can make it difficult to evaluate the specific contribution of the research (Reason and Bradbury, 2008).</p>`;
}

function ch16() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 16</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis as Research Designs</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Define systematic reviews and meta-analyses and distinguish them from narrative literature reviews<br>• Explain why systematic reviews are considered high-level evidence<br>• Describe the key steps in conducting a systematic review<br>• Understand when meta-analysis is appropriate and what it can achieve<br>• Evaluate the quality of published systematic reviews</blockquote><h2>16.1 What Is a Systematic Review?</h2>
<p>A systematic review is a research design that uses explicit, transparent, and reproducible methods to identify, select, evaluate, and synthesise all available evidence on a specific research question. Unlike a narrative or traditional literature review, which relies on the reviewer's subjective judgement about which studies to include and how to interpret them, a systematic review follows a pre-defined protocol that minimises bias and maximises the reliability of the conclusions (Higgins and Thomas, 2019).</p>
<p>Systematic reviews are considered the highest level of evidence in many fields, particularly medicine and healthcare, because they synthesise the findings of multiple primary studies into a single, comprehensive assessment. By including all relevant studies rather than a selective subset, systematic reviews provide a more complete and less biased picture of the evidence than any individual study can offer (Petticrew and Roberts, 2006).</p>
<p>The key features of a systematic review include: a clearly formulated research question, a comprehensive search strategy that aims to identify all relevant studies, explicit inclusion and exclusion criteria, systematic data extraction from included studies, critical appraisal of the quality of included studies, and a structured synthesis of the findings. These features ensure that the review is reproducible: another researcher, following the same protocol, should arrive at the same conclusions (Booth, Sutton, and Papaioannou, 2016).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 380" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THE SYSTEMATIC REVIEW PROCESS</text><rect x="120" y="55" width="300" height="38" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="270" y="79" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">1. Formulate a clear, focused question</text><line x1="270" y1="93" x2="270" y2="108" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><polygon points="265,108 275,108 270,115" fill="#999"/><rect x="120" y="115" width="300" height="38" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="270" y="139" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">2. Search comprehensively across databases</text><line x1="270" y1="153" x2="270" y2="168" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><polygon points="265,168 275,168 270,175" fill="#999"/><rect x="120" y="175" width="300" height="38" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="270" y="199" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">3. Apply inclusion/exclusion criteria</text><line x1="270" y1="213" x2="270" y2="228" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><polygon points="265,228 275,228 270,235" fill="#999"/><rect x="120" y="235" width="300" height="38" rx="6" fill="#5a4fcf"/><text x="270" y="259" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">4. Extract data and appraise quality</text><line x1="270" y1="273" x2="270" y2="288" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><polygon points="265,288 275,288 270,295" fill="#999"/><rect x="120" y="295" width="300" height="38" rx="6" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="270" y="319" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">5. Synthesise findings (narrative or meta-analysis)</text><rect x="120" y="350" width="300" height="30" rx="15" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="370" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Key: Every step is documented, transparent, and reproducible</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 16.1 The five stages of a systematic review, from question formulation to synthesis.</p></div>

<h2>16.2 Meta-Analysis</h2>
<p>Meta-analysis is a statistical technique used within some systematic reviews to combine the quantitative results of multiple studies into a single summary estimate. By pooling data from several studies, meta-analysis increases statistical power and provides a more precise estimate of the effect size than any individual study can offer (Borenstein, Hedges, Higgins, and Rothstein, 2021).</p>
<p>Meta-analysis is appropriate when the included studies are sufficiently similar in their designs, participants, interventions, and outcomes to justify combining their results. If the studies are too heterogeneous, pooling their results may produce a misleading summary estimate. Assessing heterogeneity, through statistical tests such as the I-squared statistic and through qualitative judgement about the comparability of studies, is an essential step in any meta-analysis (Higgins and Thomas, 2019).</p>
<p>The results of a meta-analysis are typically presented in a forest plot, a visual display that shows the effect size and confidence interval for each included study, along with the overall pooled estimate. The forest plot allows readers to see at a glance how consistent the findings are across studies, whether the overall effect is statistically significant, and how much individual studies contribute to the pooled estimate (Borenstein, Hedges, Higgins, and Rothstein, 2021).</p>

<h2>16.3 Systematic Review vs. Traditional Literature Review</h2>
<p>It is important to distinguish between a systematic review and a traditional (narrative) literature review. A traditional literature review is a scholarly summary of existing knowledge on a topic, written by an expert who selects, organises, and interprets the literature based on their own judgement. It is valuable for providing an overview, identifying themes, and establishing context, but it is susceptible to selection bias and subjectivity (Hart, 2018).</p>
<p>A systematic review, by contrast, uses explicit methods to minimise bias at every stage. It searches comprehensively rather than selectively, applies predetermined criteria for inclusion, appraises quality using standardised tools, and synthesises findings using transparent methods. This rigour makes systematic reviews more reliable as evidence summaries, but it also makes them more time-consuming and resource-intensive to produce (Petticrew and Roberts, 2006).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Systematic Review vs. Traditional Literature Review</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-2"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Systematic Review</h4><p>• Comprehensive search strategy<br>• Pre-defined protocol<br>• Explicit inclusion criteria<br>• Quality appraisal of each study<br>• Transparent synthesis<br>• Reproducible by others</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Traditional Literature Review</h4><p>• Selective search<br>• No formal protocol<br>• Subjective inclusion<br>• Variable quality assessment<br>• Narrative synthesis<br>• Dependent on reviewer's expertise</p></div></div></div>`;
}

